<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-21T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-21T05:00:00-05:00" n="286" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d286">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/5571:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé at Tangier (<persName type="from">Childs</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tangier</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-21T11:00:00+01:00">May
                                        21, 1942—11 a.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received 12:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>230. It may be perhaps useful to the Department to know that it is
                                the unanimous opinion of us here in Tangier including the Military
                                and Naval Attachés as well as my British colleague that at least
                                token shipments should be resumed to Morocco under the
                                American-French economic accord.</p>
                            <p>One obvious advantage of token shipments is that they offer a <hi rend="italic">raison d’être</hi> for the continued activity of
                                the control officers whose reports have contributed so much to the
                                work of Anglo-American joint intelligence center here which is
                                cooperating most effectively with Gibraltar and Malta.</p>
                            <p>By courier to Casablanca, Algiers.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Childs</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>